'''''The Courtship of Princess Leia''''' is a [[Star Wars Legends|''Star Wars'' Legends]] novel written by [[Dave Wolverton]]. It was first published in [[April]] [[1994]] by [[Bantam Spectra]]. The novel is set in [[8 ABY/Legends|8 ABY]], four [[Standard year/Legends|years]] after the events of [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Star Wars'': Episode VI ''Return of the Jedi'']], and it ends with the [[Wedding of Han Solo and Leia Organa/Legends|wedding]] of [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]] and [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia Organa]].

==Publisher's summary==
''Darth Vader and the Emperor are dead, but the Empire lives on and the Alliance must continue the struggle with dwindling supplies of cash and resources. Princess Leia, seeking rich, powerful allies to bring into the Alliance and a new planet as a home for the influential refugees of Alderaan, considers a proposal that could tip the balance of power against the evil Empire. The Hapes consortium, a cluster of sixty-three high-tech worlds, is ruled by the Queen Mother, who wants Leia to marry her son, the dashing and wealthy Prince Isolder.''

''When Han Solo hears the news of Leia's impending nuptials, he reacts with shock. Han always dreamed of marrying Leia himself, but in spite of his heroic exploits he feels that she sees him as nothing more than a shiftless rogue and Corellian pirate, unworthy of her hand. Now he makes a desperate last gamble to win her back. Tricking Leia into accompanying him, Han flees with her to the beautiful and untamed planet Dathomir, where he hopes to win her heart.''

''Fearing the imperious queen's reaction to Han's rash move, Luke Skywalker forms an unlikely alliance with Prince Isolder to track down the runaways. Luke has been traveling the far reaches of the galaxy in search of the scattered lore of the Jedi Knights. But when he, Artoo, and Isolder set off to Dathomir, Luke little suspects that it is only the beginning of an adventure that will lead to the discovery of an awesome treasure, a group of Force-trained "witches"&hellip;and a showdown with an invincible foe.''

The Courtship of Princess Leia'' relives the swashbuckling epic of the ''Star Wars'' film trilogy as starcruisers battle for control of space, knights of a forbidden order rise again, and a pirate sues for the heart of a maiden.''

==Plot summary==
[[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]], who had been aboard the ''[[Mon Remonda]]'' continuing the search for this hidden fortress, is wearily returning to the recently captured [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]] and expecting an end to the long separation from his beloved, [[Princess/Legends|Princess]] [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia]], the head of the [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]]. To his great surprise, when his vessel drops out of [[Hyperspace/Legends|hyperspace]] and into the [[Coruscant system/Legends|Coruscant system]], he encounters a number of fearsome [[Imperial-class Star Destroyer/Legends|Imperial Star Destroyers]], [[Hapan Battle Dragon]]s, and a [[Nova-class battle cruiser|''Nova''-class battle cruiser]]. Han soon learns that the [[Hapes Cluster/Legends|Hapes Cluster]] has sent a delegation of some kind to the New Republic to meet with its representative. Upon entering the [[Imperial Palace/Legends|Imperial Palace]], Han enlists the help of [[C-3PO/Legends|C-3PO]] to translate and comment on the formal [[Diplomat/Legends|diplomatic]] reception. While observing the reception, Han watches as the Hapes delegation presents Leia with a number of stunning gifts from each world in the Hapes cluster, among them the dozen Star Destroyers Han had seen, a [[Gun of Command|Hapan gun of command]], a small [[Plant/Legends|plant]] resembling a [[bonsai]] which promotes longevity and intelligence and, most shockingly of all, the hand of [[Prince/Legends|Prince]] [[Isolder]], the son of [[Ta'a Chume]] (the current ruler of the Hapes cluster), in [[Marriage/Legends|marriage]].

When Leia nearly accepts this startling proposal, Han is driven into a frenzy of fear and jealousy. Guided by his desperation, Han wanders into a dive of a [[Cantina/Legends|cantina]] in the lower reaches of Coruscant, where he participates in a high-stakes [[Sabacc/Legends|sabacc]] game. During the game, one of Han's opponents runs out of liquid financial instruments and instead proffers real estate in the form of a deed to an entire habitable [[Planet/Legends|planet]], [[Dathomir/Legends|Dathomir]]. Thinking he has found a gift which would prove his worthiness to Leia and compare favorably with the gifts of Isolder (offering to provide a place to resettle the expatriates of [[Alderaan/Legends|Alderaan]] to boot), he immediately rushes to her side to present his winnings. When Leia examines his gift and points out playfully that he has been conned (since Dathomir is in the section of [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]] controlled by [[Zsinj]]), Han is devastated. To add insult to injury, Isolder denigrates the [[Millennium Falcon/Legends|''Millennium Falcon'']] and offers Han a [[Nova-class battle cruiser|''Nova'' battle cruiser]] if he abandons his quest to win Leia's heart. This last slight is enough to drive Han over the edge; he abducts Leia using the [[Gun of Command]], and flees with her and [[Chewbacca/Legends|Chewbacca]], aboard his recently refitted ''Millennium Falcon'', to Dathomir.

Upon discovering the abduction, Prince Isolder pursues Han with his [[Hapan Battle Dragon]] and arrives at Dathomir shortly after Solo despite his head start. Isolder was able to track Han with the assistance of the [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] who had returned from his mission to [[Toola/Legends|Toola]] having found only a despoiled [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] archive. Luke [[Psychometry/Legends|read the past to find out what was up and where]], then aided Isolder by using his [[Instinctive astrogation|Force powers to navigate a shorter (but still safe) path through hyperspace]], shaving time off other conventional routes. Arriving on Dathomir, Luke and Isolder discover that Zsinj had truly laid claim to Dathomir by establishing in the planet's [[Orbit/Legends|orbit]] the [[Iron Fist (Executor-class)|''Iron Fist'']], a number of other [[Capital ship/Legends|capital ships]], and the complete orbital shipyard Han had hunted for so long.

By this time, the ''Millennium Falcon'' has been forced to land on Dathomir itself, where it is captured by the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] [[Garrison/Legends|garrison]] Zsinj had marooned on the surface [[Standard year/Legends|years]] ago. Isolder immediately sets out in his [[Miy'til starfighter]] accompanied by Luke's [[T-65 X-wing starfighter/Legends|X-wing]] while the Hapan fleet provide cover fire before leaving to inform the New Republic, [[Imperial Remnant]], and the [[Hapes Consortium/Legends|Hapes Consortium]] of the whereabouts of Zsinj (which had long been unknown).

On the surface, Isolder and Luke discover the remnants of the star-borne Jedi training academy, the ''[[Chu'unthor]]''. Luke remembers having seen recordings of [[Yoda/Legends|Yoda]] and a number of other Jedi knights failing to retrieve the library of the ''Chu'unthor'' due to interference by the [[Witches of Dathomir]]. Despite their intentions, the best the other Jedi had been able to do was seal the vessel thoroughly; so thoroughly that only [[Standard century/Legends|centuries]] later the first intruder would need a [[Lightsaber/Legends|lightsaber]] to break in. While attempting to gain access to the ship Luke is captured by a [[Dathomirian/Legends|Dathomiri]] witch. Luke and Isolder, who was also captured only moments earlier, are taken back to her village. The witch, seeing that Luke is a potent Force user, tries to get him to marry and breed with her.  Luke refuses the offer.

Meanwhile, Zsinj, who has also learned about Han Solo's presence on the planet, offers both an ultimatum and exchange to the head of the [[Nightsisters/Legends|Nightsisters]], [[Gethzerion]]. If the sisters will release Han to him to [[Torture/Legends|torture]] and [[Death/Legends|execute]] as he likes, he will reward them with an [[Lambda-class T-4a shuttle/Legends|Imperial shuttle]] to leave the planet. If they do not comply, however, he will keep his "[[Orbital nightcloak|nightcloak]]" (an interconnected network of geostationary satellites, which reflect all solar emissions back into space) intact, which will slowly freeze Dathomir until no life can continue to survive.

Han and Leia soon infiltrate the Imperial garrison and steal the ''Falcon'', piloting it out into the ongoing [[Battle of Dathomir (Hunt for Zsinj)|Battle of Dathomir]]. Han purposely allows the ''Iron Fist'' to acquire the ''Falcon'' with a [[Tractor beam/Legends|tractor beam]]; once he is within the [[Deflector shield/Legends|deflector shields]], he breaks free of the beam lock and pilots his ship over the superstructure of the gigantic vessel. Once on the main bridge, he launches two [[Concussion missile/Legends|concussion missiles]] which destroy the bridge, kill Zsinj, and knock out the ventral shields. With ''Iron Fist'' now completely exposed, the Hapan Battle Dragons move into position with their [[Ion cannon/Legends|ion cannons]], and disable the station. In the face of this catastrophic defeat and the death of the leader, [[Zsinj's Empire|Zsinj's empire]] soon crumbles.

Shortly thereafter, Solo and Leia marry, having realized during their intrepid journey together that they do indeed love each other. Isolder also gets his happy ending as it is revealed that he has fallen in love with his captor, [[Teneniel Djo]], and asks her to marry him, which she accepts.

==Development==
{{Quote|&hellip;When I heard that Leia and Han Solo had gotten married in Zahn's book, my first thought was, 'Whoa, not so fast!' There have to be some fireworks for something that significant. So I knew that I wanted to do a 'romance.'|Dave Wolverton|<ref name="Star Wars Interviews">{{WebCite|url=https://starwarsinterviews.com/various/authors/dave-wolverton-author|text=Dave Wolverton (Author)|author=Pellegrom, Dennis|work=[https://starwarsinterviews.com Star Wars Interviews]|archivedate=20200619073321|nolive=1}}</ref>}}
''The Courtship of Princess Leia'' was written by [[Dave Wolverton]] and was the author's first ''Star Wars'' novel. According to Wolverton, he had watched the [[1950s|1954]] musical film [[Wikipedia:Seven Brides for Seven Brothers|''Seven Brides for Seven Brothers'']] and became inspired to write about Leia Organa and Han Solo's marriage, which was first established in [[Timothy Zahn]]'s [[1991]] novel ''[[Heir to the Empire]]''. Wolverton wrote the novel as a "romance," and he aimed to include a sense of humor and bold ideas.<ref name="Star Wars Interviews" />

''The Courtship of Princess Leia'' was first published as a hardcover [[Bantam Spectra]] original in [[April]] [[1994]].<ref name="Amazon" />

==Continuity==
The ''Courtship of Princess Leia'' was important for the introduction of two cultures that would continue to play major roles in the [[Star Wars Legends|Expanded Universe]] and beyond: the [[Hapan|Hapans]] and the [[Witches of Dathomir]].<ref name="Essential Reader's Companion">''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]''</ref>

[[Dathomir/Legends|Dathomir]] and its magical inhabitants would influence [[George Lucas]] directly in the creation of his projects in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' universe. In [[2008]], the videogame [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars: Jedi Alliance|Clone Wars: Jedi Alliance]] used abandoned [[Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace|''Episode I'']] concept art in its striking creation of animated [[Nightsisters/Legends|Nightsisters]], which caught Lucas' attention. He used this incarnation of the Nightsisters to forge backstories for [[Asajj Ventress/Legends|Asajj Ventress]], [[Savage Opress/Legends|Savage Opress]], and [[Darth Maul/Legends|Darth Maul]] in the ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' television series, elevating Dathomir and its Witches to a higher status in the [[Canon|canon]] than in their Expanded Universe origins. The fourth-season episode "[[Massacre]]"([[2012]]) saw the Nightsisters almost wiped out, though their continued presence in the Expanded Universe later in the timeline clearly suggested that other clans did survive.<ref name="Essential Reader's Companion">''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]''</ref>

In ''Courtship'', [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke]] was repeatedly described as wielding a blue-bladed [[Lightsaber/Legends|lightsaber]], though at this point in time he was still using his green-bladed weapon. <ref name="Essential Reader's Companion">''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]''</ref>

